The Voice of Conscience

Art in motion
1948
Philippe Halsman
(Photographer)
TOI take:
Published on: Feb 20, 2025
This photograph, Dali Atomicus taken by Philippe Halsman in 1948, captures surrealist Salvador Dalí in mid-air, with flying cats, water, and floating objects. Created without digital manipulation, it required 26 takes. The image revolutionized photography by pushing creative boundaries, blending fine art and surrealism, inspiring future artists and visual storytelling.
Black power salute
1968
TOI take:
Published on: Feb 17, 2025
The black power salute during the 1968 Mexico City Olympics, captured in a powerful photograph of Tommie Smith and John Carlos, was an iconic symbol of resistance and solidarity in the fight for racial equality. This act of protest drew global attention to civil rights issues, inspiring future generations to stand up for justice.
Face of resilience
Jodi Bieber
(Photographer)
TOI take:
Published on: Feb 13, 2025
This image of Bibi Aisha, an Afghan woman disfigured by her Taliban husband and in-laws, became a global symbol of gender-based violence. It ignited worldwide outrage, amplifying conversations on women’s rights, leading to increased advocacy and policy efforts to protect and empower vulnerable women in her war-torn country.
